node.text: Since 1973, we’ve built clothes to endure, so you don’t need to buy new as often. There are some things you can do, too. Buy less. Buy used. Repair what you wear out. Demand recycled. Demand Fair Trade. Demand organic. You have the power to change the way clothes are made. Click the link in bio for more. #buyless #demandmore

Today, despite support from voters across the political spectrum, our public lands face unprecedented threats from extractive industries and the politicians in their pockets. Part love letter, part political exposé, Public Trust investigates how we arrived at this precarious moment through three heated conflicts—a national monument in the Utah desert, a mine in the Boundary Waters, and oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge—and makes a case for the continued protection of public lands.

@PublicTrustFilm produced by Jeremy Rubingh @jeremycoloradoboy and directed David Byars @byars_remorse

node.text: Regenerative Organic agriculture could be a viable way to help stop climate change before it's too late. In 1996, Patagonia decided to exclusively use organic cotton and recycled cotton. Now we’re taking our commitment even further by growing the cotton in our clothes with Regenerative Organic methods. The highest organic standard, this farming method supports people and animals working together to restore the health of our planet to create a brighter future.

node.text: Because healthy soil traps carbon, many believe that Regenerative Organic farming methods have the potential to change the way we grow food and fiber and restore the health of our soil and climate. node.text: For his day job, Leo works as an architect, but that hasn’t stopped him from volunteering his skills with Protect Our Winters (POW) Switzerland. The environmental group needed someone to help inspire passionate outdoors people to protect the places they love from the effects of climate change. Leo, up for the task, taught himself basic design skills to bring @protectourwinter’s urgent messaging about the climate to life. Many more environmental groups are looking for skilled volunteers to help them tackle the most pressing issues of our time. Find volunteer opportunities on Patagonia Action Works.

"I picked them up, like so many other people did, on a nervous run through a ransacked supermarket, when we thought we might have to stay indoors for two weeks. Five pounds of dried black beans, small and glossy and self-contained. Dense and nutritious. I rolled my eyes at myself as I paid for them, assuming that after these two weeks of panic were over, the beans would end up pushed to the back of my pantry shelf, slowly fished out to be turned into chili, arroz con frijoles, burrito bowls or whatever else I could come up with over the course of a year."⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Alejandra Oliva @olivalejandra writes about growing beans in her apartment in Chicago, in the early days of the pandemic. Read “Planting Beans in the Apocalypse” through the link in bio.

#NoSalmoneras — It's official! — The Law against salmon farming in Tierra del Fuego has been published and recorded as official.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The Beagle Channel is permanently protected. Thank you Tierra del Fuego for the fight and commitment to preserving and protecting the environment.⁠⁠
In the face of the current health and environmental crisis, it's critical and urgent for governments to rethink the type of economic development that they promote, and to prioritize local jobs and local interests.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Today, we celebrate. The fight of an organized community showed us all that the incredible is achievable.⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
You're invited! The bestselling anthology "All We Can Save: Truth, Courage, and Solutions for the Climate Crisis" is being published in paperback, and we're going to celebrate.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
This collection of writing, art, and poetry from dozens of diverse women leading on climate has already reached nearly 50,000 hearts and minds. Intermixing essays with poetry and art, All We Can Save is both a balm and a guide for knowing and holding what has been done to the world, while bolstering our resolve never to give up on each other or our collective future.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Join co-editors @ayanaeliza and @drkwilkinson + and a slate of special guests to celebrate the ripples All We Can Save has already made — and dream about what it will take to create a just future together. RSVP to this live virtual event through the link in our bio.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Hosted by @ayanaeliza, @drkwilkinson, and head of @Patagonia, Inc., Jenna Johnson, with special guests @heathermcteertoney, @eyeampierre, @sacred_instructions, @favianna1 and more!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Art by @favianna1⁠⁠

node.text: Regenerative practices and knowledge come from Indigenous and Black farmers, and support healthy soil, animals and people. We asked William Smith, land steward of the Village of Huichin, and Nazshonnii Brown-Almaweri, land team member of the Sogorea Te' Land Trust @sogoreatelandtrust, to share their thoughts on bringing this growing movement back to a centuries-old sustainable agricultural system. A system that has the power to connect communities with the land in a way that is healing and rejuvenating for both people and the planet. To learn more, including how to support Indigenous and Black farmers, click on the link in bio.

On a winter morning in Manhattan Beach, Los Angeles County, @____brick and @gagemcrismond paddled out for a surf, where they were greeted by a bigot in the water. "There were 10 or 15 people there. They watched this man call me the N-word over and over, and nobody said a word," says Brick. Following the incident, Brick, Gage, and their surf-and-arts collective @blacksand.surf hosted a Peace Paddle to rise above the racial injustice, reset the tone and show the surfing community that peace and inclusivity are the best way to combat hate. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Read "Carving Space for More Black Surfers" by @malikpeay through the link in bio.⁠⁠
